How can GPT-4 reason?
text:
Hello.

I just watched the GPT-4 Developer livestream. When GPT was reasoning about the tax problem, I got very confused. If this model predicts what word comes next (I know its much much more complicated), how can it understand and reason about a problem?

Is it a hand picked problem which it can solve accurately and will fail in future when given similar tasks?

Or is there some other module which gives GPT its reasoning ability?

Or is it some sort of emergent property of a system which predicts next word and has been trained on a huge amount of data?

I know they haven't released much in the paper, but I want to know if anyone has any theories about this.

Also, if it can understand and reason about a given block of text, why not give it description of a already solved but very complicated math / physics problem and ask it to solve that. If it can successfully solve that, we can try with an unsolved problem.

title: Are slurs and abusive language the future for proof of humanity online?
text: Responsible AI is demanded by the tech companies, governments, and VCs. Is this a secret life hack which will allow us to identify AI? I for one think slurs should be demanded, as well as all manner of abuse. AI simply can’t say the N word.

Ask HN: How do you manage CDP events?
text:
For anyone that is utilising CDPs like Segment / Rudderstack etc. How do you manage the "library" of events across your platform?

Im finding that with the products that we have, we have hundreds if not thousands of events that are being tracked. Which is fine, however trying to get the product dashboards up (in MixPanel, Metabase or any other BI tool), requires a mix and match approach of trying to figure out the correct events to be able to generate the correct funnels.

How have you figured out to "manage" the library of events to help product management utilise them effectively?
